# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: runtime-security-falco
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:runtime-security-falco/berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:runtime-security-falco/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:runtime-security-falco/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:runtime-security-falco/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP can be integrated as a framework or module that runs in conjunction with a program's codes, libraries and system calls.
[src:runtime-security-falco/runtime-application-self-protection] The technology can also be implemented as a virtualization.
[src:runtime-security-falco/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP solutions can be deployed in two different ways: monitor or protection mode.
[src:runtime-security-falco/runtime-application-self-protection] In monitor mode, the RASP solution reports on web application attacks but does not block any attack.
[src:runtime-security-falco/runtime-application-self-protection] In protection mode, the RASP solution reports and blocks web application attacks.
[src:runtime-security-falco/seccomp] seccomp mode is enabled via the `prctl(2)` system call using the `PR_SET_SECCOMP` argument, or (since Linux kernel 3.17) via the `seccomp(2)` system call. seccomp mode used to be enabled by writing to a file, `/proc/self/seccomp`, but this method was removed in favor of `prctl()`.
[src:runtime-security-falco/seccomp] In some kernel versions, seccomp disables the `RDTSC` x86 instruction, which returns the number of elapsed processor cycles since power-on, used for high-precision timing.
[src:runtime-security-falco/seccomp] Some consider seccomp comparable to OpenBSD pledge(2) and FreeBSD capsicum(4).
[src:runtime-security-falco/seccomp] seccomp was first devised by Andrea Arcangeli in January 2005 for use in public grid computing and was originally intended as a means of safely running untrusted compute-bound programs.
[src:runtime-security-falco/seccomp] It was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 2.6.12, which was released on March 8, 2005.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In computing, a **system call** (**syscall**) is the programmatic way in which a computer program requests a service from the operating system on which it is executed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] This may include hardware-related services (for example, accessing a hard disk drive or accessing the device's camera), creation and execution of new processes, and communication with integral kernel services such as process scheduling.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] System calls provide an essential interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In most systems, system calls can only be made from userspace processes, while in some systems, OS/360 and successors for example, privileged system code also issues system calls.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] For embedded systems, system calls typically do not change the privilege mode of the CPU.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The architecture of most modern processors, with the exception of some embedded systems, involves a security model.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] However, many applications need access to these components, so system calls are made available by the operating system to provide well-defined, safe implementations for such operations.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The operating system executes at the highest level of privilege, and allows applications to request services via system calls, which are often initiated via interrupts.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] An interrupt automatically puts the CPU into some elevated privilege level and then passes control to the kernel, which determines whether the calling program should be granted the requested service.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] If the service is granted, the kernel executes a specific set of instructions over which the calling program has no direct control, returns the privilege level to that of the calling program, and then returns control to the calling program.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Generally, systems provide a library or API that sits between normal programs and the operating system.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] On Unix-like systems, that API is usually part of an implementation of the C library (libc), such as glibc, that provides wrapper functions for the system calls, often named the same as the system calls they invoke.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] On Windows NT, that API is part of the Native API, in the ntdll.dll library; this is an undocumented API used by implementations of the regular Windows API and directly used by some system programs on Windows.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The library's wrapper functions expose an ordinary function calling convention (a subroutine call on the assembly level) for using the system call, as well as making the system call more modular.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Here, the primary function of the wrapper is to place all the arguments to be passed to the system call in the appropriate processor registers (and maybe on the call stack as well), and also setting a unique system call number for the kernel to call.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In this way the library, which exists between the OS and the application, increases portability.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The call to the library function itself does not cause a switch to kernel mode and is usually a normal subroutine call (using, for example, a "CALL" assembly instruction in some Instruction set architectures (ISAs)).
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The actual system call does transfer control to the kernel (and is more implementation-dependent and platform-dependent than the library call abstracting it).
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] For example, in Unix-like systems, `fork` and `execve` are C library functions that in turn execute instructions that invoke the `fork` and `exec` system calls.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] On exokernel based systems, the library is especially important as an intermediary.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] On exokernels, libraries shield user applications from the very low level kernel API, and provide abstractions and resource management.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] IBM's OS/360, DOS/360 and TSS/360 implement most system calls through a library of assembly language macros, although there are a few services with a call linkage.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] This reflects their origin at a time when programming in assembly language was more common than high-level language usage.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] IBM system calls were therefore not directly executable by high-level language programs, but required a callable assembly language wrapper subroutine.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Since then, IBM has added many services that can be called from high level languages in, e.g., z/OS and z/VSE.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In more recent release of MVS/SP and in all later MVS versions, some system call macros generate Program Call (PC).
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] On Unix, Unix-like and other POSIX-compliant operating systems, popular system calls are `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `wait`, `exec`, `fork`, `exit`, and `kill`.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Many modern operating systems have hundreds of system calls.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] For example, Linux and OpenBSD each have over 300 different calls, NetBSD has close to 500, FreeBSD has over 500, Windows has close to 2000, divided between win32k (graphical) and ntdll (core) system calls while Plan 9 has 54.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Tools such as strace, ftrace and truss allow a process to execute from start and report all system calls the process invokes, or can attach to an already running process and intercept any system call made by the said process if the operation does not violate the permissions of the user.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] This special ability of the program is usually also implemented with system calls such as ptrace or system calls on files in procfs.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Implementing system calls requires a transfer of control from user space to kernel space, which involves some sort of architecture-specific feature.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] A typical way to implement this is to use a software interrupt or trap.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Interrupts transfer control to the operating system kernel, so software simply needs to set up some register with the system call number needed, and execute the software interrupt.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] This is the only technique provided for many RISC processors, but CISC architectures such as x86 support additional techniques.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] For example, the x86 instruction set contains the instructions `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` and `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` (these two mechanisms were independently created by AMD and Intel, respectively, but in essence they do the same thing).
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] These are "fast" control transfer instructions that are designed to quickly transfer control to the kernel for a system call without the overhead of an interrupt.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Linux 2.5 began using this on the x86, where available; formerly it used the `INT` instruction, where the system call number was placed in the `EAX` register before interrupt 0x80 was executed.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] An older mechanism is the call gate; originally used in Multics and later, for example, see call gate on the Intel x86.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] It allows a program to call a kernel function directly using a safe control transfer mechanism, which the operating system sets up in advance.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] For IA-64 architecture, `EPC` (Enter Privileged Code) instruction is used.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The first eight system call arguments are passed in registers, and the rest are passed on the stack.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In the IBM System/360 mainframe family, and its successors, a Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), with the number in the instruction rather than in a register, implements a system call for legacy facilities in most of IBM's own operating systems, and for all system calls in Linux.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In later versions of MVS, IBM uses the Program Call (PC) instruction for many newer facilities.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In particular, PC is used when the caller might be in Service Request Block (SRB) mode.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The PDP-11 minicomputer used the EMT, TRAP and IOT instructions, which, similar to the IBM System/360 SVC and x86 INT, put the code in the instruction; they generate interrupts to specific addresses, transferring control to the operating system.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The VAX 32-bit successor to the PDP-11 series used the CHMK, CHME, and CHMS instructions to make system calls to privileged code at various levels; the code is an argument to the instruction.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] Within the RISC-V privileged architecture, the instruction `ECALL` (after *environment call*) is designed to enter a more privileged level and therefore this instruction performs the functionalities related to system calls.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] `ECALL` events are then handled in a similar fashion to other types of synchronous traps, including the same return mechanism.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In the related Linux implementations, the system call number is placed into the `a7` (`x17`) register before `ECALL` is executed, function arguments are listed in accordance to the RISC-V ABI (`a0`, `a1`, ...) while the return value is put in `a0`.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] System calls in most Unix-like systems are processed in kernel mode, which is accomplished by changing the processor execution mode to a more privileged one, but no *process* context switch is necessary – although a *privilege* context switch does occur.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The hardware sees the world in terms of the execution mode according to the processor status register, and processes are an abstraction provided by the operating system.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] A system call does not generally require a context switch to another process; instead, it is processed in the context of whichever process invoked it.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] In a multithreaded process, system calls can be made from multiple threads.
[src:runtime-security-falco/system-call] The handling of such calls is dependent on the design of the specific operating system kernel and the application runtime environment.
